properties.Title: freezing drizzle advisory in effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A long lasting period of freezing drizzle is expected or occuring. Periods of freezing drizzle will persist tonight then taper off on Sunday. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Freezing drizzle can produce thin, hard to detect layers of ice. Weather Advisories for Freezing Drizzle are issued when drizzle falling in sub zero temperatures is expected to freeze on contact, and over time create icy surfaces. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required. Stay up to date with Weatheradio or your local media. Email reports of severe weather to weatherNLWO@ec.gc.ca or call 1-877-815-9900. You may tweet reports using the hashtag #NLwx.

properties.Title: fog advisory in effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Near zero visiblity in fog is expected or occurring. Fog persists over central and eastern portions of southern Manitoba this afternoon, and will likely continue throughout the night due to a moist and stagnant airmass. As north winds develop on Sunday, the foggy area should gradually retreat to the southeast. Visibilities should begin to improve during the day, however in Whiteshell and Sprague this improvement will likely not arrive until Sunday evening. In addition, freezing drizzle may affect portions of southern Manitoba on Sunday as the cold air works its way in. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. If travelling, be prepared for areas of near zero visibility. Weather Advisories for fog are issued when near zero visibilities in fog are expected or occurring. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required. Please continue to monitor your local media or Weatheradio for further updates. If you would like to report severe weather, you can call 1-800-239-0484 or send an email to storm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports to #MBStorm.

properties.Title: fog advisory in effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Near zero visiblity in fog is expected or occurring. Fog persists over central and eastern portions of southern Manitoba this afternoon, and will likely continue throughout the night due to a moist and stagnant airmass. As north winds develop on Sunday, the foggy area should gradually retreat to the southeast. Visibilities should begin to improve during the day, however in Whiteshell and Sprague this improvement will likely not arrive until Sunday evening. In addition, freezing drizzle may affect portions of southern Manitoba on Sunday as the cold air works its way in. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. If travelling, be prepared for areas of near zero visibility. Weather Advisories for fog are issued when near zero visibilities in fog are expected or occurring. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required. Please continue to monitor your local media or Weatheradio for further updates. properties.Title: freezing drizzle advisory in effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Areas of freezing drizzle are expected or occuring. Freezing drizzle will continue through Sunday morning in this region. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Freezing drizzle can produce thin, hard to detect layers of ice. Take extra care when walking or driving in affected areas. Weather Advisories for Freezing Drizzle are issued when drizzle falling in sub zero temperatures is expected to freeze on contact, and over time create icy surfaces. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required. Please continue to monitor your local media or Weatheradio for further updates. If you would like to report severe weather, you can call 1-800-361-0233 or send an email to tempsviolent.quebec@ec.gc.ca. You may also tweet reports of severe weather to #meteoqc.

properties.Title: fog advisory in effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Near zero visiblity in fog is expected or occurring. Light winds and high humidity caused fog to form over the northern grainbelt of Saskatchewan as well as in the Red River Valley of Manitoba. Fog is no longer expected over southwestern Manitoba and southeastern Saskatchewan due to a thick layer of high cloud. Fog patches are possible from Meadow Lake through Saskatoon, however they are not expected to be dense or persistent. Areas experiencing dense fog such as Nipawin and Winnipeg should see visibilities gradually improve around midday. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. If travelling, be prepared for areas of near zero visibility. Weather Advisories for fog are issued when near zero visibilities in fog are expected or occurring. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required. Please continue to monitor your local media or Weatheradio for further updates. properties.Title: fog advisory in effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Near zero visiblity in fog is expected or occurring. Fog has become quite extensive across the regions, with areas of dense fog also occurring. Visibility has dropped to near zero in dense fog at Kenora Airport this morning. Areas of dense fog with zero visibility will persist across the regions until at least noon today. The fog will then slowly try to lift and become more patchy this afternoon. Motorists should be prepared for zero visibility in areas of dense fog this morning, and allow extra time to reach their destination. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. If travelling, be prepared for areas of near zero visibility. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required, so stay tuned to your local media or Weatheradio. Email reports of severe weather to storm.ontario@ec.gc.ca or tweet with the hashtag #ONStorm.
